55. Volteium nomine Menam] This person is represented as a freedman of some person of the Volteia gens, of which one or two are mentioned in the Roman writers. A freedman took the Gentile nume of his master on his manumission. The name Menas is ukin to Menodorus, as Demus to Deme- trius, Lucas to Lucanus, Silas to Sylvanus, Artemas to Artemius, etc.

56. sine crimine, notum Et] The deseri tion Menas gives of himself is, that he is a crier of small means, of unblemis ed character, well known as a per- son who could be active or quiet as the occasion required, and who enjoyed what he got; one who made himself happy in the company of humble people, in the possession of a house of his own, at the theatres and Circus, and with the amusements of the Campus Martius. ‘Et quaerere et uti,’ ‘to get and to enjoy,' expresses the reverse of him who is ‘nescius uti Compositis ' (S. ii. 3. 109). ‘Lare certo ’ is opposed to a lodging, ‘coenaculum ’ (Epp. i. l. 91, n.). It appears (v. 65) that he transacted business as a seller ; probably he had some second-hand things of his own to dispose of.
